o At a frequency determined by a risk analysis.
5. Changes to systems within the production environment, including network and security
components, should be controlled by the formal change control procedures. The change control
procedures should include but not be limited to: [Baseline]
o maintaining a record in accordance with the A5. System Logging and Monitoring;
o testing changes before deployment;
o establishing a rollback plan;
o submitting changes by authorized users;
o reviewing controls and integrity procedures to ensure that they will not be compromised
by the changes;
o identifying all software, information, database entities and hardware that require
amendment;
o identifying and checking security critical code to minimize the likelihood of known security
weaknesses;
o obtaining formal approval for detailed proposals before work commences;
o ensuring authorized users accept changes prior to implementation;
o ensuring that the system documentation set is updated on the completion of each change
and that old documentation is archived or disposed of;
o maintaining a version control for all software updates;
o maintaining an audit trail of all change requests;
o ensuring that operating documentation and user procedures are changed as necessary to
remain appropriate; and
o ensuring that the implementation of changes takes place as scheduled and does not
disturb the business processes involved.
6. Bespoke applications and package modifications must be suitably documented, and that
documentation must be updated to reflect any changes that are made, as a mandatory part of
the change control procedure. [Baseline]
7. Post-implementation review must be performed by manager of the change implementer.
[Baseline]

Ngữ cảnh: JARDINE MATHESON INFORMATION SECURITY POLICY GUIDELINES CONFIDENTIAL
Nội dung chính: [JARDINE MATHESON INFORMATION SECURITY POLICY GUIDELINES CONFIDENTIAL]
5. Apart from the JM Group Cybersecurity and Cybersecurity Interest Group, some examples of
external sources for CTI that the company can leverage are listed as follows: [Advanced]
o Information Sharing and Analysis Centres (ISACs) from around the world;
o Computer Emergency Response Team (CERT) community from around the world;
o Cybersec Infohub;
o Different commercial and open source threat intelligence feed;
o Intelligence from vendors providing services and/or products to the company.
6. The following log content can be leveraged as internal sources for CTI: [Advanced]
o Network Data Sources covering the following information
• Timestamp;
• IP address, port, and other protocol information;
• Domain name;
• TCP/UDP port number;
• MAC address;
• Hostname;
• Action (deny/allow);
• Status code;
• Network flow data;
• Packet payload;
• Type of attack (i.e. SQL injection, buffer overflow);
• Attack status (success/fail/blocked).
o Host Data Sources covering the following information
• Bound and established network connection and port;
• Process and thread;
• Registry setting;
• Configuration file entry;
• Software version and patch level information;
• Hardware information;
• User and group;
• File attribute (e.g., name, hash value, permissions, timestamp, size);
• File access;
• System event (e.g., startup, shutdown, failures);
• Command history;
• Browser history and cache;
• Malware type and actions taken by antivirus (i.e. quarantine, clean, rename,
delete).
7. CTI should include information related to geopolitical events that could increase cybersecurity
threat levels. [Advanced]

Ngữ cảnh: JARDINE MATHESON INFORMATION SECURITY POLICY GUIDELINES CONFIDENTIAL > Threat Intelligence Sharing
Nội dung chính: [Threat Intelligence Sharing]
1. The Cyber Security Team should communicate CTI with business risk context and risk
management recommendations to the business units within the company. [Baseline]
2. CTI data should be used as input to the following: [Baseline]
o Information security risk management processes;
o Technical preventive and detective controls like firewalls, intrusion detection system, or
anti malware solutions;
o Information security test processes and techniques.
3. CTI should be shared amongst the JM Group through approved channel(s) to promote situational
awareness, knowledge maturation and to improve the Group’s defensive agility and overall
security posture. NIST Special Publication 800-150 can be referenced for guidance over cyber
threat information sharing, in particular but not limited to the following sections: [Advanced]
o Define Information Sharing Goals and Objectives;
o Define the Scope of Information Sharing Activities;
o Establish Information Sharing Rules;
o Consume and Respond to Security Alerts;
o Organize and Store Cyber Threat Information.

Ngữ cảnh: JARDINE MATHESON INFORMATION SECURITY POLICY GUIDELINES CONFIDENTIAL > C1. Asset Management > C1.3. Definition
Nội dung chính: [C1.3. Definition]
Assets include the following types:
o Information resources (e.g. application data and documents);
o Software (e.g. operating systems and application software);
o Hardware (e.g. user workstations, mobile devices, network equipment, server computers, IoT
devices, peripheral equipment);
o Services (e.g. cloud services and general utilities).

Ngữ cảnh: JARDINE MATHESON INFORMATION SECURITY POLICY GUIDELINES CONFIDENTIAL > C1. Asset Management > C1.4. Policy Statements > Asset Inventory
Nội dung chính: [Asset Inventory]
1. All assets must be registered in an asset register or automated asset tracking and inventory
system to keep track of their status. [Baseline]
2. Annual stock takes of assets must be performed to ensure that the asset register or system
generated inventory records are accurate, up to date, consistent and aligned amongst each other.
[Baseline]
3. Physical assets should be tagged with adhesive identification labels where possible. [Baseline]
4. The asset inventory should at least include information listed as follows: [Baseline]
o Asset ID;
o Asset type;
o Classification;
o Location;
o Owner;
o Function / purpose;
o License information;
o Manufacturer and model;

Ngữ cảnh: JARDINE MATHESON INFORMATION SECURITY POLICY GUIDELINES CONFIDENTIAL
Nội dung chính: [JARDINE MATHESON INFORMATION SECURITY POLICY GUIDELINES CONFIDENTIAL]
o Machine serial number;
o Host name (if applicable);
o IP address (if applicable);
o OS type and version (if applicable);
o Sub-system (if applicable);
o Asset status;
o Status date.
5. Assets that are in scope for PCI DSS should be tagged and clearly identifiable as such in the
inventory. [PCI]
6. An asset management tool should be deployed to collect and manage inventory and
configuration data from all company’s hardware and software assets. [Advanced]
7. The supply chain risk should be reviewed before the acquisition of mission-critical information
systems including system components. [Advanced]

Ngữ cảnh: JARDINE MATHESON INFORMATION SECURITY POLICY GUIDELINES CONFIDENTIAL > D1. Logical Access Management > D1.3. Definition
Nội dung chính: [D1.3. Definition]
Different account types include the followings:
o Regular user account;
o Privileged user account such as root account, administrator account;
o Guest / Temporary user account;
o Non-user account such as service accounts.

Ngữ cảnh: JARDINE MATHESON INFORMATION SECURITY POLICY GUIDELINES CONFIDENTIAL > Multi-factor Authentication
Nội dung chính: [Multi-factor Authentication]
1. Multi-factor authentication must be required for more sensitive roles and access such as:
[Baseline]
o Domain Administrator;
o Enterprise Administrator;
o Network access to secure zones;
o Active Directory privilege activities (i.e. Group Policy Object changes, schema changes);
o Human Resources Management System;
o Administrator and end-user access to all cloud-based platforms, applications and security
tools, including Office 365, e-mail gateways, file storage services, social media accounts,
etc.;
o Internet facing systems that allow access to sensitive data, such as VPN, Webmail, etc and
general users, such as cloud file storage services.
2. Multi-factor authentication must be enforced for non-console access to card data environment.
[PCI]

Ngữ cảnh: JARDINE MATHESON INFORMATION SECURITY POLICY GUIDELINES CONFIDENTIAL > F1. 3rd Party / Vendor Management > F1.3. Definition
Nội dung chính: [F1.3. Definition]
Third party / external service providers and vendors comprise any external personnel who provide or
perform any sorts of products or services to and for the company. Such personnel should have, but not
limited to, the following characteristics:
o have access to the company’s network;
o hold copies of the company’s information;
o responsible for hosting any company information system assets in their own network, cloud or
data centre;
o in some other way would store, transfer or process the company’s information.

Ngữ cảnh: JARDINE MATHESON INFORMATION SECURITY POLICY GUIDELINES CONFIDENTIAL > Managing Changes of Outsourcing Services
Nội dung chính: [Managing Changes of Outsourcing Services]
1. Changes to the provision of services provided by external service providers should be properly
reviewed, approved and documented by all relevant stakeholders. The followings should be taken
into consideration: [Baseline]
o Changes to the agreements;
o Changes made by the company;
o Changes made by the external service provider;
o Risk level of the change.

Ngữ cảnh: JARDINE MATHESON INFORMATION SECURITY POLICY GUIDELINES CONFIDENTIAL
Nội dung chính: [JARDINE MATHESON INFORMATION SECURITY POLICY GUIDELINES CONFIDENTIAL]
o Data fields that each grade of staff in the user department are allowed to access;
o The way that each grade of staff in the user department are allowed to manipulate the
data in the computer files;
o Level of audibility required;
o Amount of data to be maintained and the purpose of maintaining it in the information
system;
o Data files that need to be backed-up;
o Number of copies of backup to be maintained;
o Frequency of backup and archive.
5. The following security principles and secure coding practices should be observed and referenced
to relevant guidelines (i.e. D1. Logical Access Management, A2. System Hardening) when
designing and developing applications and APIs: [Baseline]
a. Secure architecture, design and structure;
b. Least privilege;
c. Segregation of duties;
d. Secure the weakest link;
e. Proper authentication and authorisation;
f. Proper session management;
g. Input validation;
h. Proper error handling;
i. Reject further code execution if application failure occurs;
j. Proper configuration management;
k. Data confidentiality;
l. Data authenticity and integrity;
m. Secure deployment.
6. Data Protection Impact Assessment (DPIA) must be conducted if the system has significant privacy
implications (i.e. the system is used to host or process Confidential / Highly Confidential
information as referenced to the C4. Information Security Classification). [Baseline]
7. All interdependencies between systems, applications and services should be identified and
reviewed for adequacy. [Advanced]

Ngữ cảnh: JARDINE MATHESON INFORMATION SECURITY POLICY GUIDELINES CONFIDENTIAL > System Development
Nội dung chính: [System Development]
1. The followings must be considered when assessing the risks associated with application
development: [Baseline]
o The sensitivity of data to be processed, stored and transmitted;
o Applicable internal and external requirements from regulations or policies;
o Trustworthiness of working staff;
o The level of outsourcing (if any) associated with application development, as referenced
to the F1. 3rd Party / Vendor Management;
o Whether segregation between different development environments is necessary;

Ngữ cảnh: JARDINE MATHESON INFORMATION SECURITY POLICY GUIDELINES CONFIDENTIAL > H2. Wireless Security > H2.3. Definition
Nội dung chính: [H2.3. Definition]
Wireless networks are usually recognised to be less secure than Ethernet. Some of the common attacks
against wireless networks are listed as follows:
o Rogue Wireless Devices;
o Peer-to-peer Attacks;
o Eavesdropping;
o Encryption Cracking;
o Authentication Attacks;
o MAC Spoofing;
o Management Interface Exploits;
o Wireless Hijacking.

Ngữ cảnh: JARDINE MATHESON INFORMATION SECURITY POLICY GUIDELINES CONFIDENTIAL > I1. Incident Response > I1.3. Definition
Nội dung chính: [I1.3. Definition]
Incident is defined as an information security event(s) which present a real and present danger to the
confidentiality, integrity or availability of company information. Information security event is used to
describe occurrences which have the potential to become or generate an incident.
Digital forensics includes the recovery, analysis and investigation of evidence or materials found in digital
devices. Forensic investigation constitutes, but is not limited to, the following cases where digital evidence
may be collected:
o employee/vendor/guest internet misuse/abuse;
o employee email misuse/abuse;
o employee/vendor performance issues;
o electronic bullying/harassment;
o data breach;
o cyber-attack;
o formal law enforcement agency/legal request for digital evidence;
o fraud.

Ngữ cảnh: JARDINE MATHESON INFORMATION SECURITY POLICY GUIDELINES CONFIDENTIAL > C5. Information Security Handling and C2. Asset Disposal. [Baseline]
Nội dung chính: [C5. Information Security Handling and C2. Asset Disposal. [Baseline]]
11. The following background information should be prepared prior to the forensic investigation:
[Advanced]
o Description of the incident and imaging / preservation needs;
o Roles and responsibilities;
o Relevant contact details (i.e. Technical and Legal personnel);
o System types and Operating Systems;
o Size of data to be collected.

Ngữ cảnh: JARDINE MATHESON INFORMATION SECURITY POLICY GUIDELINES CONFIDENTIAL > L1. Personnel Security > L1.4. Policy Statements > Prior to Employment
Nội dung chính: [Prior to Employment]
1. Appropriate checks in accordance with existing HR policy on all applications for employment,
including all contractors and temporary staff, where access to information assets and handling of
sensitive information is required. The background check must include the following: [Baseline]
o applicant’s curriculum vitae;
o reference letters, if any;
o academic and professional qualifications;
o identity documents;
o reasons for leaving the company, if the applicant is an ex-employee;
o criminal records or court records where legally permitted;
o verification of employment details with former employers.
2. Background checks must be conducted in accordance with data privacy and employment laws,
with written consent obtained in advance where necessary. [Baseline]
3. Screening process for contractor provided by an external party should be managed by the project
manager. [Baseline]
4. Users of information assets must be required to sign an appropriate information security policy
compliance undertaking as part of their initial conditions of employment. This must include an
appropriate confidentiality clause that has been reviewed by Group Legal or the company's legal
representative. [Baseline]

